&lt;p&gt;One of the aspects I really like about KNX is that it is a brand-agnostic protocol, which makes it very easy to find any kind of object compatible with it.
Another aspect that KNX has, different from many other options, is that it is it bus based.
Being bus-based is a huge pain when you have to install it, but once you have done it, the experience is way better, since there is no perceptible delay, no risk of interference, etc., making the day-to-day experience indistinguishable from a traditionally cabled system.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Red Hat EX374 exam</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2025/11/13/red-hat-ex374-exam</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2025_11_13_red_hat_ex374_exam.webp"/><pubDate>Thu, 13 Nov 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2025/11/13/red-hat-ex374-exam</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;Earlier this month, I sat the Red Hat EX374 exam to renew my Red Hat Certified Specialist in Developing Automation with Ansible Automation Platform certification.
As I’m already a Red Hat Certified Architect and have passed this same exam a couple of years ago, I wasn’t too worried about it.
Still, it is always interesting to see how exams evolve.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When I registered for the exam, I quickly checked the Objectives and remembered that it covered both Ansible core content (playbooks, modules, roles) and a lot of Ansible Automation Platform (AAP) capabilities, such as controllers, collections, and execution environments.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Leverage Event Driven Ansible to reduce your automation reaction time</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2025_11_05_gs_uk_eda</link><pubDate>Wed, 05 Nov 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2025_11_05_gs_uk_eda</guid><description/></item><item><title>Simplifying container orchestration with Ansible and Podman</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2025_11_04_gs_uk_podman</link><pubDate>Wed, 05 Nov 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2025_11_04_gs_uk_podman</guid><description/></item><item><title>bootc 101: dalla container image alla tua distro personale</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2025_10_25_bootc</link><pubDate>Sat, 25 Oct 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2025_10_25_bootc</guid><description/></item><item><title>AWS SSA-C03 exam</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2025/10/16/aws-ssa-c03-exam</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2025_10_16_aws_ssa_c03_exam.webp"/><pubDate>Thu, 16 Oct 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2025/10/16/aws-ssa-c03-exam</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;Three years passed from the &lt;a href="https://fale.io/blog/2022/10/30/aws-ssa-c03-exam/"&gt;last AWS exam&lt;/a&gt; I took, and my AWS certifications were due for renewal.
The first thing I checked was the exam code, which I had taken three years ago.
It turns out that last time I took the &lt;code&gt;SAA-C03&lt;/code&gt;, and this time I would also have taken the same exam.
This time around, I considered doing the &lt;code&gt;SAP-C02&lt;/code&gt; instead, but, given the very limited time, I decided on the &lt;code&gt;SAA-C03&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Moving out of AWS</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2025/09/18/moving-out-of-aws</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2025_09_18_moving_out_of_aws.webp"/><pubDate>Thu, 18 Sep 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2025/09/18/moving-out-of-aws</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;For years, I hosted this blog and several other services on AWS.
AWS is powerful, but it is also expensive and deeply entropic.
It often feels like every problem on AWS has three different services as possible solutions.
Each service has its own setup, and keeping track of everything just gets harder over time.
For personal infrastructure, the financial and cognitive cost simply stopped being worth it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That&amp;rsquo;s why I decided to close my AWS account and move everything somewhere else.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Red Hat EX457 exam</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2025/08/31/red-hat-ex457-exam</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2025_08_31_red_hat_ex457_exam.webp"/><pubDate>Sun, 31 Aug 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2025/08/31/red-hat-ex457-exam</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;Last week, I renewed my &lt;a href="https://www.redhat.com/en/services/training/ex457-red-hat-certified-specialist-in-ansible-network-automation-exam"&gt;Red Hat Certified Specialist in Ansible Network Automation (EX457)&lt;/a&gt; certification.
As I&amp;rsquo;m already a Red Hat Certified Architect and have passed this same exam a couple of years ago, I wasn&amp;rsquo;t too worried about it.
Still, it is always interesting to see how exams evolve.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Since I did not remember the kind of content that was there last time, I read the objectives page and assumed it would have been more on the networking side.
But, in reality, the exam leaned much more toward Ansible playbooks, modules, and automation patterns than network-specific plumbing.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>On your providers business models</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2025/06/30/on-your-providers-business-models</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2025_06_30_on_your_providers_business_models.webp"/><pubDate>Mon, 30 Jun 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2025/06/30/on-your-providers-business-models</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;When buying a service, you&amp;rsquo;re not just buying what&amp;rsquo;s on the label.
You&amp;rsquo;re buying into someone else&amp;rsquo;s business model.
This aspect is now becoming even more relevant, considering that many times, when buying a product, you are also buying a service with it since there are more and more hybrid products.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you don&amp;rsquo;t understand how your provider is structured and how it makes money, you will not fully understand your relationship with them.
