&lt;h2 id="common-europe-congress-2025-gothenburg-june-24"&gt;Common Europe Congress 2025 (Gothenburg, June 2–4)&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Common Europe Congress is the largest educational convention for IBM Power users in Europe.
This year it&amp;rsquo;s taking place at the Gothia Towers in Gothenburg, Sweden.
I&amp;rsquo;ll be there from June 2nd through the 4th, and I have two sessions lined up:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Route traffic across Podman networks with Traefik</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2025/04/30/route-traffic-across-podman-networks-with-traefik</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2025_04_30_route_traffic_across_podman_networks_with_traefik.webp"/><pubDate>Wed, 30 Apr 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2025/04/30/route-traffic-across-podman-networks-with-traefik</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;If you&amp;rsquo;ve followed my posts over the years, you know I prefer clean solutions to less clean ones for my home lab (more to come on this!).
Over the past year, I settled on a pattern that gives me the isolation of Kubernetes Namespaces without any of its weight: one private Podman network per application, plus Traefik in a shared &amp;ldquo;DMZ&amp;rdquo; network that terminates TLS and forwards traffic where it needs to go.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Where does your Ansible code come from?</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2025_04_30_gse_ansible_supply_chain</link><pubDate>Wed, 30 Apr 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2025_04_30_gse_ansible_supply_chain</guid><description/></item><item><title>Modernize mainframes workloads with Red Hat OpenShift Platform</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2025_04_29_gse_openshift</link><pubDate>Tue, 29 Apr 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2025_04_29_gse_openshift</guid><description/></item><item><title>Massimizza i tuoi investimenti con un'automazione autonoma (EDA)</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2025_04_15_webinar_eda</link><pubDate>Tue, 15 Apr 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2025_04_15_webinar_eda</guid><description/></item><item><title>Your fast track to IT automation genius with AWS and Red Hat</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2025_04_01_webinar_aws</link><pubDate>Tue, 01 Apr 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2025_04_01_webinar_aws</guid><description/></item><item><title>Fedora on Scaleway Dedibox with bootc</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2025/03/31/fedora-on-scaleway-dedibox-with-bootc</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2025_03_31_fedora_on_scaleway_dedibox_with_bootc.webp"/><pubDate>Mon, 31 Mar 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2025/03/31/fedora-on-scaleway-dedibox-with-bootc</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;For a while now, I&amp;rsquo;ve been looking into optimizing and reorganizing some of the infrastructure that powers my self-hosting services.
After evaluating a few alternatives, Scaleway&amp;rsquo;s Dedibox lineup caught my attention: it is a European company with good hardware and decent pricing.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;However, as with every good solution, it is not perfect.
Scaleway does not provide Fedora as an OS option for their Dedibox machines.
They offer a decent selection, including Rocky Linux, Debian, and Ubuntu — but no Fedora.
Now, if you know me, you know that Fedora is not just my distro of choice — it&amp;rsquo;s the one I trust for both personal and professional projects.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>How does Ansible Automation help in automating mainframe operations?</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2025_03_04_techxchange_z_ansible</link><pubDate>Tue, 04 Mar 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2025_03_04_techxchange_z_ansible</guid><description/></item><item><title>Leverage Event-Driven Ansible to reduce your automation reaction time</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2025_02_04_cfgmgmtcamp_ansible_eda</link><pubDate>Tue, 04 Feb 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2025_02_04_cfgmgmtcamp_ansible_eda</guid><description/></item><item><title>Simplifying container orchestration with Ansible and Podman</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2025_02_03_cfgmgmtcamp_ansible_podman</link><pubDate>Mon, 03 Feb 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2025_02_03_cfgmgmtcamp_ansible_podman</guid><description/></item><item><title>Upcoming Events: CentOS Connect, FOSDEM, and CfgMgmtCamp</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2025/01/31/upcoming-events-centos-connect-fosdem-and-cfgmgmtcamp</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2025_01_31_upcoming_events_centos_connect_fosdem_and_cfgmgmtcamp.webp"/><pubDate>Fri, 31 Jan 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2025/01/31/upcoming-events-centos-connect-fosdem-and-cfgmgmtcamp</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;The next few days are shaping up to be packed with open-source goodness!
I&amp;rsquo;ll be heading to CentOS Connect, FOSDEM, and CfgMgmtCamp, three of the best events in the ecosystem.
These conferences always include a great mix of technical talks, hallway conversations, and spontaneous meetups with friends—both old and new.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you&amp;rsquo;re around, let&amp;rsquo;s catch up!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;CentOS Connect&lt;/strong&gt; (Brussels, January 31)&lt;br&gt;
Although the event run yesterday and today, I&amp;rsquo;ll only be able to attend today.
CentOS Connect is a small but incredibly valuable event where the wider CentOS community (Fedora, CentOS, and all the Enterprise Linux distros) meets to discuss the space&amp;rsquo;s present and future.
It&amp;rsquo;s a great opportunity to meet contributors, learn about upcoming changes, and exchange ideas with people who shape the CentOS ecosystem.
I really like this event because its atmosphere is similar to Flock: very casual and more like a friends&amp;rsquo; gathering than a conference.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>A bad year for open source databases</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2024/12/31/a-bad-year-for-open-source-databases</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2024_12_31_a_bad_year_for_open_source_databases.webp"/><pubDate>Tue, 31 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2024/12/31/a-bad-year-for-open-source-databases</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;Although the definitions of Open Source are related to specific software characteristics (i.e., the license), the reality is much more complex.
Open-source is way more related to a social contract that the software&amp;rsquo;s creator and its users morally sign than the definition might lead you to believe.
This social contract&amp;rsquo;s key aspect concerns the software&amp;rsquo;s current license and the licenses of future versions.
This is because although users of open-source software usually do not pay to use it, they incur high costs to do so.
Examples of those costs are training costs and potential costs to replace a certain technology should it become unavailable in the future.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Introduzione all'automation con Red Hat Ansible</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2024_12_16_techxchange_power_ansible</link><pubDate>Mon, 16 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2024_12_16_techxchange_power_ansible</guid><description/></item><item><title>Where does your Ansible code come from?</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2024_12_04_opensourceexperience_ansible_supply_chain</link><pubDate>Wed, 04 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2024_12_04_opensourceexperience_ansible_supply_chain</guid><description/></item><item><title>Hyperscalers are not serious about Service Level Agreements (SLA)</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2024/11/30/hyperscalers-are-not-serious-about-service-level-agreements-sla</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2024_11_30_hyperscalers_are_not_serious_about_service_level_agreement_sla.webp"/><pubDate>Sat, 30 Nov 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2024/11/30/hyperscalers-are-not-serious-about-service-level-agreements-sla</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;I often talk with people about Service Level Agreements (SLAs) in public cloud contexts, and I discover that their idea of what those SLAs are is often distorted.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I believe SLAs need to be approached with a healthy dose of skepticism.
In reality, they often provide little meaningful recourse when things go awry.
There are two big issues, in my opinion, with the SLA provided by many companies, including the hyperscalers:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Modernize mainframes workloads with Red Hat OpenShift Platform</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2024_11_07_gse_openshift</link><pubDate>Thu, 07 Nov 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2024_11_07_gse_openshift</guid><description/></item><item><title>Modernize operations with Red Hat Ansible Automation Platform</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2024_11_07_gse_ansible</link><pubDate>Thu, 07 Nov 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2024_11_07_gse_ansible</guid><description/></item><item><title>Leverage Event Driven Ansible to reduce your automation reaction time</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2024_11_06_gse_eda</link><pubDate>Wed, 06 Nov 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2024_11_06_gse_eda</guid><description/></item><item><title>Nebula VPN split configuration</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2024/10/31/nebula-vpn-split-configuration</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2024_10_31_nebula_vpn_split_configuration.webp"/><pubDate>Thu, 31 Oct 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2024/10/31/nebula-vpn-split-configuration</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;We have had Nebula VPN within the Fedora repositories for a couple of years.
A couple of months ago, I changed the default systemd service unit.
More specifically, this is the change:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="highlight"&gt;&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma"&gt;&lt;code class="language-diff" data-lang="diff"&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="gd"&gt;-ExecStart=/usr/bin/nebula -config /etc/nebula/config.yml
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="line"&gt;&lt;span class="cl"&gt;&lt;span class="gd"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="gi"&gt;+ExecStart=/usr/bin/nebula -config /etc/nebula
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Although the change is only a few characters, this change allows for a much more flexible use of Nebula.
Before this change, the configuration could only be placed in the &lt;code&gt;config.yaml&lt;/code&gt; file.
After this change, all YAML files in the folders will be read, merged, and used as configuration.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Dal cloud al self-hosting</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2024_10_26_self_hosting</link><pubDate>Sat, 26 Oct 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2024_10_26_self_hosting</guid><description/></item><item><title>La strada verso l'immutabilità di sistemi Linux</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2024_10_26_immutable_linux</link><pubDate>Sat, 26 Oct 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2024_10_26_immutable_linux</guid><description/></item><item><title>Migliora la gestione dei container con Event-Driven Ansible</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2024_10_10_contaiener_day_ansible_eda</link><pubDate>Thu, 10 Oct 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2024_10_10_contaiener_day_ansible_eda</guid><description/></item><item><title>On being the cheapest cloud</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2024/09/30/on-being-the-cheapest-cloud</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2024_09_30_on_being_the_cheapest_cloud.webp"/><pubDate>Mon, 30 Sep 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2024/09/30/on-being-the-cheapest-cloud</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;Recently, I heard a pitch from a public cloud company.
Among other characteristics, a key aspect they stressed is that they are the cheapest cloud.
This aspect struck me.
Not because I believe it is or is not, but because I&amp;rsquo;ve heard many companies pitch themselves as the cheapest cloud over the years.
I asked the CTO if they were foreseeing consistent and planned cuts in the pricing every year or so.
The CTO&amp;rsquo;s answer was very sensible but negative on the specific point.
