&lt;p&gt;In this book, you&amp;rsquo;ll work with the latest release of Ansible and learn how to solve complex issues quickly with the help of task-oriented scenarios. You&amp;rsquo;ll start by installing and configuring Ansible on Linux and macOS to automate monotonous and repetitive IT tasks and learn concepts such as playbooks, inventories, and roles. As you progress, you&amp;rsquo;ll gain insight into the YAML syntax and learn how to port between Ansible versions. Additionally, you&amp;rsquo;ll understand how Ansible enables you to orchestrate multi-layer environments such as networks, containers, and the cloud.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Modernize IBM Z with Red Hat Ansible Automation Platform</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2023_09_21_z_ansible</link><pubDate>Thu, 21 Sep 2023 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2023_09_21_z_ansible</guid><description/></item><item><title>How does Ansible Automation help in automating mainframe operations?</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2023_09_19_z_ansible</link><pubDate>Tue, 19 Sep 2023 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2023_09_19_z_ansible</guid><description/></item><item><title>Use per-host SSH key pairs on AWX and Ansible Automation Controller</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2023/09/18/use-per-host-ssh-key-pairs-on-awx-and-ansible-automation-controller</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2023_09_18_use_per_host_ssh_key_pairs_on_awx_and_ansible_automation_controller.webp"/><pubDate>Mon, 18 Sep 2023 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2023/09/18/use-per-host-ssh-key-pairs-on-awx-and-ansible-automation-controller</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;One of the aspects that I have always loved about Ansible is that it integrates very nicely with the rest of the system where it is running.
For example, you can easily configure all the SSH configurations directly by changing the &lt;code&gt;~/.ssh/config&lt;/code&gt; file.
I&amp;rsquo;ve seen multiple cases where the SSH configuration file needs to be tweaked.
A case that comes up occasionally is an environment configured in a way that requires Ansible to use a different SSH key for each machine it manages.
I&amp;rsquo;m aware that this is not an ideal setup since it is not increasing the security as much as the person who came up with such a rule was expecting.
Still, it is a requirement that some companies have for various historical reasons and, usually, it is impossible or impractical to challenge.
