How did we arrive here, and what&amp;rsquo;s to come?
Let&amp;rsquo;s start from understanding who decides the maximum lifetime of certificates and many other limitations around them.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="who-decides-the-tls-certificate-guidelines"&gt;Who decides the TLS certificate guidelines&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Ultimately, the client (often a browser or an operating system) identifies the certificate as trustable or not (based on the CA that signed it as well as many other parameters), so the client can decide which parameters to look for and which values are acceptable and which are not.
This clients&amp;rsquo; freedom makes the whole situation very messy since every client can decide their own set, and a subset of the options accepted by every client can be very small if not empty.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>KubeCon + CloudNativeCon Europe 2020</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2020/08/20/kubecon--cloudnativecon-europe-2020</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2020_08_20_kubecon_eu_2020.webp"/><pubDate>Thu, 20 Aug 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2020/08/20/kubecon--cloudnativecon-europe-2020</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;This year I managed to partecipate to KubeCon + CloudNativeCon Europe 2020.
As you can imagine, the conference did not happen in real life, but it was converted to an online conference.
More virtual conferences I attend to, more I understand the limits and the advantages of them compared to real conferences.
In this particular conference, I realized that one of the biggest problems I have with virtual conferences is that, during the conference, the conference events and talks add to your usual events and meetings, making it impossible to follow all events you wanted to follow.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Fedora Nest 2020</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2020/08/10/fedora-nest-2020</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2020_08_10_fedora_nest_2020.webp"/><pubDate>Mon, 10 Aug 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2020/08/10/fedora-nest-2020</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;This year Flock did not happen due to COVID-19, and in its place, Fedora Nest happened.
