This will help you to use Ansible to interact with different operating systems and improve your working efficiency.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>GoLang vanity urls on AWS Lambda</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2019/03/21/golang-vanity-urls-on-aws-lambda</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2019_03_21_golang_vanity_urls_on_aws_lambda.webp"/><pubDate>Thu, 21 Mar 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2019/03/21/golang-vanity-urls-on-aws-lambda</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;After the &lt;a href="https://fale.io/blog/2019/01/18/reasons-to-prefer-vanity-urls-for-golang-packages/"&gt;article on the reasons to use vanity URLs in Go&lt;/a&gt; and the one about &lt;a href="https://fale.io/blog/2018/09/23/a-lightweight-approach-to-go-vanity-import-paths/"&gt;how to implement a lightweight vanity URLs provider&lt;/a&gt;, I&amp;rsquo;d like to share with you how you can leverage AWS Lambda to implement a vanity URLs provider.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The first thing we will need is to import the &lt;code&gt;github.com/aws/aws-lambda-go&lt;/code&gt; package.
This package will provide us with the needed functions to easily integrate our Go code with AWS Lambda.
In our &lt;code&gt;main&lt;/code&gt; we will just need to start the Lambda with a handler like this:&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>FOSDEM 2019</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2019/02/04/fosdem-2019</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2019_02_04_fosdem_2019.webp"/><pubDate>Mon, 04 Feb 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2019/02/04/fosdem-2019</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;This year, as it has happened for the last few years, I&amp;rsquo;ve been at FOSDEM.
As always I&amp;rsquo;ve enjoyed it a lot, and that&amp;rsquo;s why I continue to go there, and every time I have to suggest other people which events to attend in Europe, I always mention FOSDEM as the main event.
This year, differently from previous editions, I tried to stick to a single room both days, being mostly in the Go room on Saturday and in the Containers room on Sunday.
I made this decision since I&amp;rsquo;ve seen the advantages of last year experience, where being in the same room for a whole day allowed me to follow more talks and to stress less.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Reasons to prefer vanity URLs for GoLang packages</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2019/01/18/reasons-to-prefer-vanity-urls-for-golang-packages</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2019_01_18_reasons_to_prefer_vanity_urls_for_golang_packages.webp"/><pubDate>Fri, 18 Jan 2019 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2019/01/18/reasons-to-prefer-vanity-urls-for-golang-packages</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;Golang forces its users to use the repository URL of the dependency in the import statement.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For instance, if we want to import the “test” package that is hosted at &lt;code&gt;github.com/fale/test&lt;/code&gt;, we will need to use &lt;code&gt;github.com/fale/test&lt;/code&gt;.
On the one hand, this is very nice since it allows anyone reading the code to immediately understand where the code is hosted and therefore find it very quickly.
Also, this URL-based import path guarantees that no two different packages can have the same import path, preventing this kind of confusion for both programmers and the compiler itself.
On the other hand, this is a limitation since it makes the code very reliant on the repository location.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Calling a SOAP service in Go</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2018/12/03/calling-a-soap-service-in-go</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2018_12_03_calling_a_soap_service_in_go.webp"/><pubDate>Mon, 03 Dec 2018 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2018/12/03/calling-a-soap-service-in-go</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;Today the IT world is very focused on high performance, high throughput interfaces.
