With Ansible Tower 3.1 this is no longer the case, since all Ansible Tower machines are active all the time.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>libVirt on Hetzner</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2017/04/26/libvirt-on-hetzner</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2017_04_26_libvirt_on_hetzner.webp"/><pubDate>Wed, 26 Apr 2017 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2017/04/26/libvirt-on-hetzner</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;After many years of using Hetzner as a server provider, and having rented from them multiple servers for many reasons, I decided to rent a server with 128Gb of RAM to do some tests with many (virtualized) machines on top of CentOS.&lt;/p&gt;
