Today I&amp;rsquo;ve requested the stable branch for Fedora 23 and in the next few days I&amp;rsquo;ll do the same for Fedora and EL7.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Why am I writing about it instead of just leaving the updates come to you with the classical &amp;ldquo;dnf update&amp;rdquo;? Simply because this is a huge and very interesting update.
The biggest change in this update has been the switch from Qt4 to Qt5.
It should be pretty stable since qBittorent has been able to compile against Qt5 for more than one year and Fedora already has a lot of Qt5 packages.
So why waiting for such a long period before switching Qt version in Fedora packages?
We decided to respect the upstream decision to wait, so we switched to the Qt5 dependency when they did it.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Fedora 23</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2015_11_23_fedora23</link><pubDate>Mon, 23 Nov 2015 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2015_11_23_fedora23</guid><description/></item><item><title>FLOSS for companies, the public sector, and schools</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2015_10_24_floss</link><pubDate>Sat, 24 Oct 2015 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2015_10_24_floss</guid><description/></item><item><title>Open Street Map</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2015_10_24_osm</link><pubDate>Sat, 24 Oct 2015 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2015_10_24_osm</guid><description/></item><item><title>OpenStack Cloud Security</title><link>https://fale.io/publication/openstack_cloud_security</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/publication/openstack_cloud_security.jpg"/><pubDate>Tue, 28 Jul 2015 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/publication/openstack_cloud_security</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;OpenStack is a system that controls large pools of computing and networking resources, along with cloud storage, allowing its users to provision resources through a user-friendly interface.
OpenStack helps developers with features such as rolling upgrades, federated identity, and software reliability.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You will begin with basic security policies, such as MAC, MLS, and MCS, and explore the structure of OpenStack and virtual networks with Neutron.
Next, you will configure secure communications on the OpenStack API with HTTP connections.
You will also learn how to set OpenStack Keystone and OpenStack Horizon and gain a deeper understanding of the similarities/differences between OpenStack Cinder and OpenStack Swift.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Implementing Cloud Design Patterns for AWS by Marcus Young (Packt Publishing)</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2015/07/19/implementing-cloud-design-patterns-for-aws-by-marcus-young-packt-publishing</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2015_07_19_implementing_cloud_design_for_aws.webp"/><pubDate>Sun, 19 Jul 2015 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2015/07/19/implementing-cloud-design-patterns-for-aws-by-marcus-young-packt-publishing</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;Today the IT world is moving very quickly from the classic infrastructure with servers, switches, hard disks and so on to virtual infrastructures, where all those things are simple pieces of software faking to be real objects.
This has huge benefits, and this is why so many companies are doing this.
Along with the advantages, this new way of doing IT has it&amp;rsquo;s criticality that the administrators have to know to prevent possible problems to happen.
A lot of books that speaks about cloud technology forget to start from the basics of cloud and very often skip these concepts.
This book does not, and I greatly appreciated it.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Logjam attack</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2015/05/20/logjam-attack</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2015_05_20_logjam_attack.webp"/><pubDate>Wed, 20 May 2015 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2015/05/20/logjam-attack</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;Today it was published a new kind of downgrade attack against TLS: logjam.
The attack relies on the fact that for Diffie-Hellman key exchanges, a prime is necessary.
Many applications use a pre-generated prime to speed up the Diffie-Hellman process.
Using a pre-generated prime is not a security issue by itself, but it can become one if coupled with a server that accepts very short Diffie-Hellman keys such as the 512 bits ones (the maximum allowed for DHE_EXPORT).&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Elettronica Libera</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2015/03/21/elettronica-libera</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2015_03_21_elettronica_libera.webp"/><pubDate>Sat, 21 Mar 2015 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2015/03/21/elettronica-libera</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;Today ViGLug organized the &amp;ldquo;Elettronica Libera&amp;rdquo; (free, as-speech, electronics) event in Settala.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the morning, we had many sessions, and the focus was more on the general public and promoting those ideas with non-expert people.
In the morning, many topics were covered, such as the various boards available, Linux, and the open-source software around them.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the afternoon, the focus moved to more advanced topics, such as GPIO, OpenWrt, the networking bits, as well as a hands-on session.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Experiment with the BeagleBoard</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2015_03_21_beagleboard</link><pubDate>Sat, 21 Mar 2015 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2015_03_21_beagleboard</guid><description/></item><item><title>GNU/Linux in the enterprise world</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2015_03_21_floss</link><pubDate>Sat, 21 Mar 2015 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2015_03_21_floss</guid><description/></item><item><title>Keynote</title><link>https://fale.io/talk/2015_02_06_keynote</link><pubDate>Fri, 06 Feb 2015 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/talk/2015_02_06_keynote</guid><description/></item><item><title>LinuxDay 2014 in Melzo</title><link>https://fale.io/blog/2014/11/03/linuxday-2014-in-melzo</link><media:content type="image/webp" medium="image" width="728" height="350" url="https://fale.io/img/posts/2014_11_03_linux_day.webp"/><pubDate>Mon, 03 Nov 2014 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://fale.io/blog/2014/11/03/linuxday-2014-in-melzo</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;In Italy every year, during the last weekend of October, there is the Linux Day, an “open day” for the LUGs where they create events to publicize GNU/Linux and the Free Software.
